<div align="right"><font face="Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif"><small>DearbornDesigns</small></font></div><center><font face="Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif"><b><big><big>Learningoasis</big></big></b></font></center><font face="Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif">Picturedabove is a draft layout of an "outdoor classroom" ... "focused onchildren's emotional, physical and mental development."</font>
<h1>Baxter school yard slated to become an 'outdoor classroom'</h1><font face="Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif"><small>Posted May 1,2012</small></font><br><br>Baxter Central is among 11 Simcoe County publicelementary schools whose primary grade playground will be transformedinto "outdoor spaces focused on children's emotional, physical andmental development" in a first phase roll-out.<br><br>In his report to the Simcoe County District School Board's (SCDSB)Buildings and Facilities Standing Committee, which meets tomorrow nightin Midhurst, John Dance, Superintendent of Facilities Services,explains the "outdoor classrooms" concept runs in conjuction with FullDay Kindergarten (FDK) / Early Learning Program (ELP) which "explicitlyincorporates outdoor experiences into the daily play-based programmingdesigned to meet the learning needs of young children."<br><br>"Traditionally, outdoor play spaces have consisted of open areas forchildren to run and have fresh air. This traditional perspective limitsthe possibilities of the out of doors for student learning," writes Mr.Dance. "With the implementation of FDK staff recognize the need tocreate outdoor space for children in the primary division where theycan enjoy opportunities to play while they use their imaginations andalso meet ministry learning expectations."<br><br>The Board has retained Lexi Dearborn from Dearborn Designs to createlandscape designs, which will be presented and shared with the 11school communities for comments and suggestions later this spring.<br><br>Each of the designs are to incorporate eleven elements identified ascritical areas of focus for outdoor play. The elements are: DramaticPlay, Music, Transportation/Gross Motor, Line Games, Sand Play, WaterPlay, Outdoor Classroom, Visual Arts, Native tree species (for shadeand science), and Gardens (to create natural boundaries and to providestudents with opportunities to plant and experience life cycles),according to the report.<br><br>"Having these components within the primary areas enables children toplay and learn in large and small groups and independently.Imagination, motor skills, and an awareness of the natural world arekey to ensuring that each school has these elements included in theirplay yards. These spaces will be available for use by the entireprimary division, allowing the integration of many age groups andcreating many social opportunities that currently do not exist."<br><br>Mr. Dance suggests The SCDSB would be the first board in Ontario toactively create such outdoor spaces.<br><br>Educators in the SCDSB will be supported in the implementation of thisinitiative with curriculum resources that will provide suggestions ofways to use the areas effectively. The projects undertaken in thisinitiative are very exciting and will benefit children for years tocome.<br><br>"Following the completion of these projects, designs will be createdfor the other schools implementing phase three of Full DayKindergarten. The eventual outcome is that outdoor classrooms will bedeveloped as each phase of the Full Day Kindergarten program isimplemented."
